    <br />

    
    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Cloning and Functional Expression of Amorpha-4, 11-Diene Synthase, a Key Enzyme in Artemisinin Biosynthesis from Artemisia Annua in to Cichorium Intybus</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Ahameethunisa.A</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Functional Expression<br />Cichorium Intybus</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Oct-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0080</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Malaria is one of the life threatening, mosquito-borne infectious human diseases caused by the apicomplexa parasite from the genus Plasmodium. The parasite Plasmodium is transmitted from infected person to healthy person via a bite by infected female mosquito of the genus Anopheles. If not treated with effective antimalarial drug, malaria can quickly become life-threatening by disrupting the blood supply to vital organs.
In many parts of the world, malarial parasites have developed resistance to most of the antimalarial medicines. Resistance of P. falciparum to choloroquine, the commonly used drug and other antimalarial drugs is spreading in almost all the malarial endemic countries. Chloroquine resistance is a major cause of worldwide increases in malaria mortality and morbidity.
Artemisinin (Qinghaosu), a sesquiterpene lactone with a peroxide bridge linkage, is isolated from the Chinese herb Artemisia annua L. Artemisinin is recognized as a new generation of effective antimalarial drug used in the combination treatments along with conventional monotherapies. Artemisinin-based combination therapies are most preferred for their enhancement of efficacy to lower malarial incidence and their potential to lower the rate at which resistance emerges and spreads.
Although artemisinin is effective in the treatment of drug resistant malaria, the bioaccumulation of artemisinin in A. annua leaves ranges from 0.01 to 0.8% of dry weight. The exponential increase in the number of countries adopting ACTs has led to rapid increase in demand and shortage in global supply. Drug cost of ACTs is the biggest obstacle in convincing policy-makers in poor developing countries to adopt ACTs. In spite of high cost, the supply of artemisinin and its derivatives used in
ii
ACTs regiment is only about half of global need. Therefore, there is increasing need to find an alternative source and improved strategies to satisfy the large and increasing global requirement and demand for this important life saving compound.
Since artemisinin is a complex molecule, its chemical synthesis is not economical. Tremendous efforts have been devoted with an aim to improve artemisinin content in the plant and production of it by heterologous E. coli and yeast expression in system. In addition, tomato, potato and tobacco as heterologous systems for the production of artemisinin are under development by many research groups. Production of artemisinin or precursors of artemisinin compounds made using microbial systems or nonfood crops is more encouraging as they can be used for direct human consumption. The development of a new host genetically engineered for increased production of artemisinin, which could be grown as a cropping plant in the area where the drug is actually required, would thus be of great value.
The main component of this thesis is to identify and develop a heterologous plant for the production of artemisinin precursor and thereby increasing the yield of artemisinin. The sesquiterpene synthase (SQS) enzymes play multifaceted active roles in the most complex biosynthetic reactions. SQSs enzymes are capable of producing many sesquiterpene skeletons. SQS is considered as a rate limiting step as it located at the branching point for terpene metabolism. The first committed step in artemisinin biosynthesis is the conversion of farnesyl diphosphate (FPP) to amorpha-4,11-diene (AMD) by SQS, amorpha-4,11-diene synthase (ADS). The in silico prediction of a heterologous system by comparatively analyzing ADS with other SQS from related plant species having similar type of cyclization activity for the biosynthesis of sesquiterpene lactones is carried out. Evolutionary relationships among the selected SQSs where analyzed. The SQSs were homology modeled as the
iii
three-dimensional structure determined by crystallography is not available for the proteins in the SQSs family. The modeled proteins were studied for the binding interaction posses among the farnesyl diphosphate. As the sesquiterpene synthases catalyse the metal dependent turnover of farnesyl diphosphate, the modeled proteins were incorporated with Mg2+ metal ions. Docking was performed in modeled SQSs in the presence (closed) and absence (open) of Mg2+ ions.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/8054">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/8054</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
